This is the LAST piece I currently have available, created this past spring 💛 I’ve taken a break from making jewelry this summer, and it’s been highly needed.

New pieces are coming soon though! I just received a bunch of new wire, and will be trying out different techniques and ways of approaching my art. 
I’ve felt stuck in the same pattern of creating for some time now, and this break has very much re-inspired me to get back to creating unique and genuine pieces. 🥰

I would highly encourage anyone feeling stuck in the mud, or suffering from “artists block” to take at least a month off to revaluate what it is that YOU want to get and feel from your own work, I promise it will do nothing but help 💚

The 1960's can be seen as a turning point in modern artistic development. Not only did the changing political climate bring along developments in visual art and music; the 1960's also saw the advent of astonishing modern  glasswork. 
Although tucked behind the iron curtain, glass makers in Czechoslovakia seized the opportunity to reflect the modern shapes of the mid-century period into their glass designs. 
This brought about a wide and diverse array of unique handmade glassware with a truly timeless touch. 
We at KayaGlass aim to tell the story of these unique colorful pieces. Follow us to find out more!

🤓We funa have a history lesson yall, and to help illustrate this lesson i will be displaying in-depth angles of my initial paradolia thesis work and then my og iconuggraphic work. I will be posting these while i work on a very special project behind the scenes. I will do my best to explain each work in a concise manner but keep it open to free interpretation. Which is what art is all about, especially my black and white work. My 2D work has always been about how visual textures can be decontextualized and reconjoined to manipulate the interpreted forms in a fashion that can even speak to a surreal mythical story via symbolic forms carrying ambiguous but real weight in our minds' eye. that of which must "recognizes" things. Although in my initial works with multiple fabrics as reference, i purely experimented with light and maluable form to see how far my pencil stroke could go. how many uncertain yet specific and accurate forms can be rendered and reinterpreted. via such a simple tool as well. this drawing here was only the beginning of a long journey towards my reunion with Pi and his evolution to Pi137. This drawing is called "It All Depends", only using an  unerasable black color pencil. I referenced one single shirt over and over in an organic way and grew around this large sheet of paper to finally come across an image of this Domo, Teddy like face with 2 fushigi balls on either side to play with the fabric that surrounds it. I was seeing where it could go. It was a playful yet disciplining experience. I truley fell in love with black color pencils at this moment. Feel free to ask questions, although i may still have as many questions as you have lol
either way, enjoy the view
goodnight and goodmorning
